problem_prompt: Approach the following question the way someone with a PhD in biology would. Find the imaginary part of \[(\cos12^\circ+i\sin12^\circ+\cos48^\circ+i\sin48^\circ)^6.\]
gpt_response:
To find the imaginary part of the expression \[\left(\cos12^\circ+i\sin12^\circ+\cos48^\circ+i\sin48^\circ\right)^6,\] we will first expand the expression using the binomial theorem. Each term will have a combination of a cosine and sine term raised to the power of 6, and we need to find the imaginary part of this expression.

By expanding the expression, we get
\[\begin{aligned}&(\cos12^\circ+i\sin12^\circ+\cos48^\circ+i\sin48^\circ)^6 \\&= \sum_{k=0}^{6}\binom{6}{k}(\cos12^\circ)^{6-k}(i\sin12^\circ)^k(\cos48^\circ)^k(i\sin48^\circ)^{6-k} \\ &= \binom{6}{0}(\cos12^\circ)^6(i\sin12^\circ)^0(\cos48^\circ)^0(i\sin48^\circ)^6 \\ &+ \binom{6}{1}(\cos12^\circ)^5(i\sin12^\circ)^1(\cos48^\circ)^1(i\sin48^\circ)^5 \\ &+ \cdots \\ &+ \binom{6}{6}(\cos12^\circ)^0(i\sin12^\circ)^6(\cos48^\circ)^6(i\sin48^\circ)^0 \\ &= (\sin48^\circ \sin12^\circ)^6 \\ &+ 6(\cos48^\circ\sin12^\circ\sin48^\circ\cos12^\circ)^5(\sin12^\circ)^{1}(\sin48^\circ)^{1} \\ &+ \cdots \\ &+ (\cos12^\circ \cos48^\circ)^6,\end{aligned}\]
where we used the fact that $i^2=-1$ and $i^3=-i$ in the expansion.

The imaginary part will be given by the terms containing $i$ in the expansion. Thus, the imaginary part of the expression is
\[6(\cos12^\circ\sin48^\circ\sin12^\circ\cos48^\circ)^5(\sin12^\circ)^{1}(\sin48^\circ)^{1} = 6(\sin 36^\circ)^5\sin12^\circ\sin48^\circ.\]

Therefore, the imaginary part of the expression is $\boxed{6(\sin 36^\circ)^5\sin12^\circ\sin48^\circ}$.
